<subsubsection xml:id="quick-ref-if"><title>Integrating Factor</title>

	<worksheet><title>Key Terms &amp; Concepts</title>

		<p>
			<assemblage><title>✳️ Integrating Factor</title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li xml:id="p1-summary-first-order-linear-de"><title>First-Order Linear Differential Equation</title>
							<p>
								These equations take the standard form:
								<me>
									y' + P(x)y = Q(x).
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="p1-summary-integrating-factor"><title>Integrating Factor</title>
							<p>
								A function, <m>\mu</m>, multiplied onto the standard form, above, to reverse the product rule, leading to the equation, <m>\mu' = P\mu</m>, with the solution
								<me>
									\mu = e^{\int P(x) dx}.
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="p1-summary-if"><title>Integrating Factor Method</title>
							<p>
								A solution method for first-order linear equations that uses an integrating factor to convert the equation into a form solvable by direct integration.
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</p>
		
	</worksheet>

</subsubsection>